ual Employee Resilience</strong> </p>\r\n<p>Like organisations individual employees also have resilience capacity. However, in most cases organisations have no control over events that impact on employees outside the work environment, even though those very events (issues relating to finances, relationships, health etc) may indirectly impact at work. Consequently an holistic approach to building resilience capacity needs to take into account both individual and organisational requirements.\r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="col-md-12 m_t2">\r\n<p><strong>1.2 HOW RESILIENCE HELPS AN ORGANISATION?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Being resilient can provide organisations with a competitive advantage. Following a disruption an organisation with a higher degree of resiliency is more likely to return to a productive state than those who do not view organisational resilience as part of core business. A resilient organisation effectively aligns its strategy, operations, management systems, governance structure and decision support capabilities so that it can uncover and adjust to continually changing risks, endure disruptions to its primary earnings drivers, and create advantages over less adaptive competitors. Inherent in this approach is to ensure a supportive employee culture within the organisation.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="col-md-12 m_t2"><strong>1.3 Our Resilience Services:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Organisational resilience audits\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Resilience questionnaire and baseline measurements</li>\r\n	<li>Aligning strategy, operations and systems</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Resilience coaching</li>\r\n	<li>Workshops&amp; WebEx vignettes\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building Resilient Teams</li>\r\n	<li>Stress &amp; Resilience</li>\r\n	<li>Energiser programs</li>\r\n	<li>Resilience Strategies for Managers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="col-md-12 m_t2"><p><strong>1.4 Stress Management </strong></p>\r\n<p>The negative effects of stress can cause considerable damage to work performance, learning and well-being of the employee. Consequently this can then impact negatively on workplace productivity. This is seen in increasing absenteeism, presenteeism, workers compensations costs, workplace conflict all of which work against the outcomes the organisation is seeking. Our stress management interventions will ensure greater safety, well-being and performance of your workforce while improving the productivity of the whole organisation.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="col-md-12 m_t2"><p><strong>1.5 Mindfulness and workplace engagement </strong></p><p>Engagement in our work matters. Low levels of engagement impact productivity and our sense of self-esteem. Most modern workplaces are undergoing constant change. Some far reaching and some subtle but all impacting to lesser or greater extent on employees. When substantive changes to our work (design, reporting duties etc.) occurs, we often need targeted mechanisms that provide employees with alternate pathways aimed at empowering them to take positive steps to reappraise their own circumstances. We have designed a number of workplace mindfulness programmes that focus on teaching employees the importance of taking responsibility for what is occurring in the present, and responding in ways that enhanced personal wellbeing and greater workplace engagement.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'Mental Health, Sleep & Fatigue Management', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '77-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-07-06 05:22:57', '2015-07-06 05:22:57', '', 77, 'http://111.93.163.213/SMGHealth/php/77-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
